4. README-ready thesis

Thesis

Most systems model human networks as static nodes and edges.
That loses the thing that matters most: change over time.

OrbitOS models each actor as a bounded state vector moving through a shared relational field. Interactions are treated as perturbations, alignments, repulsions, or couplings that alter future trajectory. The result is not a graph of who knows whom, but a dynamical map of who changes whom, how strongly, and in what direction.

⸻

5. Canonical primitives

These need to be crisp.

Actor

A bounded representation of a person, team, org, or institution.

Actor {
  actor_id: str
  actor_type: Literal["person", "team", "org", "system"]
  embedding: Vector
  state_vector: Vector
  velocity_vector: Vector
  mass_profile: MassProfile
  boundary_profile: BoundaryProfile
  visibility_policy: VisibilityPolicy
  metadata: dict
}

StateVector

Snapshot of actor position in modeled space at time T.

Contains things like:
	•	topical orientation
	•	behavioral tendencies
	•	decision style
	•	communication rhythm
	•	stability / variance
	•	declared goals
	•	inferred directionality
	•	confidence intervals

InteractionEvent

A time-stamped perturbation between actors.

InteractionEvent {
  event_id: str
  timestamp: datetime
  source_actor_id: str
  target_actor_id: str
  interaction_type: str
  magnitude: float
  valence: float
  confidence: float
  payload_ref: Optional[str]
}

Field

The shared environment in which actors move.

Contains:
	•	ambient context
	•	institutional constraints
	•	trend pressure
	•	market conditions
	•	cultural drift
	•	group norms

Orbit

The time-series trajectory of an actor through state space.

Resonance

Sustained phase alignment between two or more actors.

Perturbation

A measurable deviation in expected trajectory caused by interaction or context shock.

⸻

6. Physics model, translated into engineering

Do not pretend this is literal astrophysics. Frame it as a field-inspired dynamical model.

Force decomposition

For actor i under influence of actor j:

\Delta x_i(t+1) = \Delta x_i(t) + F_{align} + F_{repel} + F_{couple} + F_{context} + \epsilon

Where:

Alignment force

Pull from shared goals, trust, similarity, repeated coordination.

Repulsion force

Push from threat, conflict, rivalry, status competition, value divergence.

Coupling force

Synchronized movement due to contracts, teams, routines, rituals, shared incentives.

Context force

Macro pressure from market, institution, platform, culture, life events.

Noise term

Unobserved variance and measurement error.

That is repo-safe language. It says what it is without pretending to have solved social reality.

⸻

7. What “mass” should mean

Do not define mass as followers. That would poison the whole system.

Use a composite:

MassProfile {
  attention_mass: float
  coordination_mass: float
  decision_mass: float
  narrative_mass: float
  dependency_mass: float
}

Interpretation:
	•	attention_mass = ability to attract notice
	•	coordination_mass = ability to align others into action
	•	decision_mass = ability to change resource flow or outcomes
	•	narrative_mass = ability to shape interpretation
	•	dependency_mass = extent to which other trajectories rely on them

That is much stronger than “influence score.”

⸻

8. What “distance” should mean

Distance is not physical, and not just semantic similarity.

Use composite manifold distance:

d(i,j)=w_1 d_{belief}+w_2 d_{behavior}+w_3 d_{goal}+w_4 d_{tempo}+w_5 d_{role}

Dimensions might include:
	•	belief distance
	•	behavior distance
	•	incentive distance
	•	timing / cadence distance
	•	status / role distance
	•	mission distance

That gives you a defensible interpretation layer.

⸻

9. Observable phenomena

These are the outputs that make the product useful.

Orbital capture

An actor’s trajectory becomes dominated by another actor or system.

Resonance lock

Two actors stabilize into repeated mutual reinforcement.

Drift

Trajectory changes without clear intentional thrust; often environmental.

Ejection event

Actor exits a cluster after accumulated perturbation exceeds binding strength.

Lagrange zone

Stable niche between dominant actors or institutions.

Identity well

A basin of behavioral recurrence that is hard to leave.

Chaos band

Region where prediction confidence drops sharply due to volatility or conflict.

Shadow coupling

Indirect influence through shared audiences, incentives, or memetic overlap.

These are memorable and product-legible.

⸻

10. World-ready guardrails

This is the difference between a serious system and a dangerous toy.

Non-negotiable rules

1. No claim of full personhood capture

Always state:

OrbitOS models observable trajectory proxies, not the totality of a human being.

2. No covert surveillance framing

Only ingest:
	•	user-provided data
	•	organizationally authorized data
	•	public data with explicit disclosure
	•	opt-in telemetry

3. No manipulation optimization mode

Do not optimize for:
	•	coercion
	•	persuasion targeting against vulnerable states
	•	social pressure exploitation
	•	reputational sabotage
	•	partner/friend/family control

4. Human override and explanation required

No important decision should be made solely from orbit outputs.

5. Visibility tiers

Actors should have visibility policies:
	•	private self-view
	•	team-visible aggregated view
	•	org-visible anonymized view
	•	public mode only with strong abstraction

6. Confidence must be visible

Every rendered inference should expose:
	•	confidence
	•	evidence basis
	•	data freshness
	•	known blind spots

